 B  |        |        | extra  |         |  F11   |        |        |        |
    |   -    |   ]    | ret    |         |        |   )    |        |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   +    |        |        |   NP    |  CRSR  |   NP   |        |        |
 C  |        |        |        |         |        |        |        |        |
    |   =    |        |        |   .     |   UP   |   /    |        |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   |    |   NP   |   NP   |   NP    |  CRSR  |   NP   |        |        |
 D  |        |        |        |         |        |        |        |        |
    |   \\    |   1    |   4    |   7     |  DOWN  |   *    |        |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |        |   NP   |   NP   |   NP    |  CRSR  |   NP   | PAUSE  |        |
 E  |        |        |        |         |        |        |        |        |
    |        |   2    |   5    |   8     |  RIGHT |   +    | BREAK  |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|
    |   NP   |   NP   |   NP   |   NP    |  CRSR  |        |        |        |
 F  |        |        |        |         |        |  HELP  |  F12   |        |
    |   0    |   3    |   6    |   9     |  LEFT  |        |        |        |
----|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|--------|--------|--------|

@endnode

@node "MAST" "Meridian - Main set-up"

@{MS "Main set-up"}

Well, there isn't much to say! Use the cursor keys for selecting and the return key for entering
the @{"hotkey set-up" link "Edit"}.@{par}

Here're the gadgets of the preferences program:@{par}
@{code}
@{MS "Miscellaneous set-up"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Global Set-Up" link "MASTGlob"}
@{MS "Meridian set-up"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Meridian List" link "MASTLIST"}
@{"New..." link "MASTNEWI"}
@{"Copy..." link "MASTCOPY"}
@{"Edit..." link "MASTEDIT"}
@{"Remove..." link "MASTDELE"}

@{"Save" link "MASTSAVE"}
@{"Use" link "MASTOKOK"}
@{"Cancel" link "MASTCANC"}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAsT"} @{"Edit Window" link "Edit"} @{"Global Set-Up" link "Glob"}

@endnode
@node "MASTGlob" "Meridian - Global Set-up..."
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Global Set-up..."}

This button opens the @{"Meridian Set-up" link "Glob"} window.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MASTLIST" "Main Set-up - The Meridian List"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "The Meridian List"}

This list contains all user defined meridians. By pressing return or using the
@{"edit" link "MASTEDIT"} gadget you are able to @{"edit" link "Edit"} the meridian.
The @{"new" link "MASTNEWI"} gadget allows to add a new meridian and the @{"remove" link "MASTDELE"} gadget
allows to delete the active one!

@endnode
@node "MASTNEWI" "Main Set-up - New..."
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "New..."}

Creates a new meridian and opens the @{"Meridian Set-up" link "Edit"} window for the meridian.@{par}

@{b}Aborting the @{"Meridian Set-up" link "Edit"} window causes the new entry to be removed.@{ub}@{par}


@endnode
@node "MASTCOPY" "Main Set-up - Copy..."
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Copy..."}

This button clones the current entry and opens the @{"Meridian Set-up" link "Edit"} window.

@{b}Aborting the @{"Meridian Set-up" link "Edit"} window causes the new entry to be removed.@{ub}@{par}


@endnode
@node "MASTEDIT" "Main Set-up - Edit..."
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Edit..."}

By pressing on this button the @{"edit" link "Edit"} window opens and allows you to change the
meridian settings.

@endnode
@node "MASTDELE" "Main Set-up - Remove..."
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Remove..."}

After a safety request the selected meridian will be removed from list!

@endnode
@node "MASTSave" "Main Set-up - Save"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Save"}

The settings will be saved into Meridians icon and used as well. The hotkey configuration will be
stored in the ENV: directory. All Meridian windows will close immediately.

@endnode
@node "MASTOkOk" "Main Set-up - Use"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Use"}

The window will be closed and the settings used, but the settings won't be saved!

@endnode
@node "MASTCanc" "Main Set-up - Cancel"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Cancel"}

This button closes the window and all changed settings are lost!

@endnode

@node "Edit" "Meridian - Meridian Set-up"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Meridian Set-up"}

This window allows to set-up a @{"meridian" link "FAQSMeridian"}. Just press and
hold the @{"Qualifier" link "GlobQual"}, move the mouse up and release the
Qualifier to finish Meridian detection. You just defined your first virtual
hotkey.@{par}

Just type in a command or key combination within the commands set-up and you're
ready to use it. Try to create angles, squares and lines. The white arrow is the
starting point and you have to move the mouse in the same direction displayed in
the meridian display to activate action. Starting a another edge of the square
is creating a complete different meridian. By painting a full square it's
possible to create 8 different meridians by changing starting point and
direction. Single line meridians can be used in two directions, too.@{par}

It doesn't matter where you "paint" the meridian on the screen, but make sure to
move a good distance. Moving only a very small distance complicates the
detecting process, because a diagonal line may be seen as a 90 degree
angle.@{par}

It's possible to create very complex elements. Feel free to use them on your own
risk, since you must be very good in repeating the same meridian. I suggest to
use the 1 arrow combinations first. Then the two arrow version with 90 and 45
degree angle. A rotating "U" is also very use full. By using these you get 40
easy to use Meridians. Full squares or combinations like "left, right, left" or
"left, right, left, right" are very handy, too. Just play around and find your
personal favorites.@{par}

@{code}
@{MS "Key Set-up"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Name" link "EditName"}
@{"Meridian Information" link "EditInfo"}
@{"Task" link "EditTask"}
@{MS "Command Set-up"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Execute Type" link "EditExTy"}
@{"Stack" link "EditStac"}
@{"Command" link "EditComm"}
@{"Current Directory" link "EditCuDi"}
@{"Output File" link "EditOuFi"}
@{"Use" link "EditOkOk"}
@{"Cancel" link "EditCanc"}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAsT"} @{"Edit Window" link "Edit"} @{"Global Set-Up" link "Glob"}

@endnode
@node "EditName" "Meridian Set-up - Name"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Name"}

Here you can specify a special name for the meridian.@{par}

The name will only be used for the @{"meridian list" link "MASTLIST"}!

@endnode
@node "EditInfo" "Meridian Set-up - Meridian Information"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Meridian Information"}

This text output field shows meridian error messages.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditTask" "Meridian Set-up - Task"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Task"}

By using this gadget you can bind a Meridian to a specific task. By doing this the same meridian
can be used in different programs to cause different action.@{par}

Meridian is comparing from the end of the task name. If you specify "golded" it
will match with "t:golded" as well as with a task named "golded:golded"@{par}

The easiest way to specify task is to use the pop up gadget next to the input
field and select the task name from list. Many known and non use tasks are removed and others are simplified
to make selections as easy as possible.@{par}

A meridian without a task gets active if non other identical meridian is
matching with a task. E.g. there are two meridians with an arrow straight up.
One has the task "Golded", the other hasn't a task specified. The meridian with
"golded" gets only active in GoldED. The other gets active in any other
situation.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditExTy" "Meridian Set-up - Execute type"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Execute type"}

This gadget allows to set-up what type of command is specified in the @{"command" link "EditComm"} gadget.@{par}

Currently "CLI", "WB", "Key", "Arexx" and @{"Macro" link "Macros"} are available.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditStac" "Meridian Set-up - Stack"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Stack"}

This gadget specifies the stack for the @{"command" link "EditComm"}.

@endnode
@node "EditComm" "Meridian Set-up - Command"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Command"}

The contents of this gadget depends on the @{"execute type" link "EditExTy"}:

@{MT "CLI / WB / ARexx"}

Path and command name of the command you want to execute.

@{MT "Key"}

This gadget contains a new key combination. Please note that key groups like "SHIFT" are not
allowed. It's required to specify the key. So define "LSHIFT", "RSHIFT" or "CAPSLOCK" instead.@{par}

Meridian is using the qualifier without any modifications. So a "CONTROL LALT HELP" is used even
if the user is pressing the shift key! Sometimes it may be useful to let the user qualifier through.
Let's say you want the Help key as a replacement for an "a". It's required that you're able to type
a "A" (shift) or an "Š" (alt). The "-" version of a qualifier in indicating that the specified
qualifier is path through. In our case the key command looks like this: "-LSHIFT -RSHIFT -LALT -RALT
-RCOMMAND -RCOMMAND -CONTROL -CAPSLOCK a".

@{MT "Macro"}

Meridian is supporting a lot of @{"Macro" link "Macros"}-functions for usage,
which can be selected via a popup list, too.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditCuDi" "Meridian Set-up - Current Directory"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Current Directory"}

If you want to change the current directory for the @{"command" link "EditComm"}, then put it in
here.

@endnode
@node "EditOuFi" "Meridian Set-up - Output File"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Output File"}

The output of the command can be redirected by using this gadget.

@endnode
@node "EditOkOk" "Meridian Set-up - Use"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Use"}

The hotkey settings will be used and the edit window will be closed.

@endnode
@node "EditCanc" "Meridian Set-up - Cancel"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Cancel"}

Closes the edit window! All changes will be rejected.

@endnode

@node "Glob" "Meridian - Global Set-up"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Global Set-up"}

This window allows to configurate the global Meridian set-up.@{par}
@{code}
@{MS "Miscellaneous Set-up"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Filter" link "GlobFilt"}
@{"Exact" link "GlobExac"}
@{"Double" link "GlobDoub"}
@{MS "Qualifier Set-up"}
@{JCENTER}@{"Qualifier" link "GlobQUAL"}
@{"Use" link "GlobOkOk"}
@{"Cancel" link "GlobCanc"}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAsT"} @{"Edit Window" link "Edit"} @{"Global Set-Up" link "Glob"}

@endnode
@node "GlobFilt" "Global Set-up - Filter"
@toc "Glob"

@{MS "Filter"}

During Meridian detection the pointer won't be moved!@{par}

@{b}This feature should only be activated when you're an advanced meridian user, because
you'll lose any visible information.@{par}

It's not possible to filter the left and right mouse button, when specified alone, because
in such case drag and drop and menu operations aren't possible any more.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "GlobExac" "Global Set-up - Exact"
@toc "Glob"

@{MS "Exact"}

When setting this switch any non activation qualifier will cause the detection to abort
and no new detection is possible until these "wrong" qualifiers are gone. So if
@{"Shift" link "GLOBQUAL"} is selected, the ALT key is not allowed!@{par}

@endnode
@node "GlobDoub" "Global Set-up - Double"
@toc "Glob"

@{MS "Double"}

This switch allows to use a double click with the specified qualifier to
activate a meridian. It's not required to double click with any selected
@{"qualifiers" link "GlobQUAL"}. Just pick the easiest and perform the click with it. Normally this
would be the mouse button.@{par}

If you for example specified the left shift key and the middle mouse button as
qualifier, then press and hold the shift key and double click with the mouse
button.@{par}

Here a small example on how activate a @{"meridian" link "FAQSMeridian"} in double mode. the qualifier is
the middle mouse button. Push it and release. Push it again, hold it and move
the mouse to draw the meridian. Finally release the button.@{par}

The timing between the two qualifier clicks is important. If you find it to
difficult to activate the meridian, open the AmigaOS input preferences and
change the timing to your needs.@{par}

@endnode
@node "GlobQUAL" "Global Set-up - Qualifier"
@toc "Glob"

@{MS "Qualifier"}

The displayed qualifier is required to activate the meridian detection.@{par}

@{b}The fourth, fifth and sixth mouse button is only usable when using a mouse
connected via PS2m hardware. When using Amithlon you're able to set-up "shift" or
"alt" as 4th mouse button and choose the same as qualifier for meridian.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "GlobOkOk" "Global Set-up - Use"
@toc "Glob"

@{MS "Use"}

The global settings will be used.

@endnode
@node "GlobCanc" "Global Set-up - Cancel"
@toc "Glob"

@{MS "Cancel"}

Closes the window! All changes will be rejected.

@endnode

@node "GeLw" "The List Selection Window"

@{MS "The List Selection Window"}

This window allows to select a specific entry of a given list.@{par}

@endnode

@node "Macros" "Macros"

@{MS "Macros"}

Macros are small functions, which can be specified as action by a simple
selection.@{par}

@{JCenter}
The following Macros are supported:@{par}

@{b}Screen Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"ScreenNext" link "MacrosScreenNext"}*@{par}
@{"ScreenPrev" link "MacrosScreenPrev"}*@{par}
@{"WBToFront" link "MacrosWBToFront"}*@{par}

@{b}Window Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"WindowBottomLeft" link "MacrosWindowBottomLeft"}*@{par}
@{"WindowBottomRight" link "MacrosWindowBottomRight"}*@{par}
@{"WindowCenter" link "MacrosWindowCenter"}*@{par}
@{"WindowClose" link "MacrosWindowClose"}@{par}
@{"WindowControl" link "MacrosWindowControl"}*@{par}
@{"WindowMaximise" link "MacrosWindowMaximise"}*@{par}
@{"WindowMinimise" link "MacrosWindowMinimise"}*@{par}
@{"WindowMove" link "MacrosWindowMove"}*@{par}
@{"WindowNext" link "MacrosWindowNext"}*@{par}
@{"WindowPrev" link "MacrosWindowPrev"}*@{par}
@{"WindowToBack" link "MacrosWindowToBack"}*@{par}
@{"WindowToFront" link "MacrosWindowToFront"}*@{par}
@{"WindowTopLeft" link "MacrosWindowTopLeft"}*@{par}
@{"WindowTopRight" link "MacrosWindowTopRight"}*@{par}
@{"WindowZip" link "MacrosWindowZip"}*@{par}

@{"ReqOk" link "MacrosReqOk"}*@{par}
@{"ReqCancel" link "MacrosReqCancel"}@{par}

@{b}Mouse Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"MouseClick" link "MacrosMouseClick"}@{par}
@{"MouseMove" link "MacrosMouseMove"}@{par}

@{b}System Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"ColdReboot" link "MacrosColdReboot"}@{par}
@{"WarmReboot" link "MacrosWarmReboot"}@{par}

@{b}Clipboard Operations@{ub}@{par}

@{"Cut" link "MacrosCut"}@{par}
@{"Copy" link "MacrosCopy"}@{par}
@{"Paste" link "MacrosPaste"}@{par}

@{b}Miscellaneous@{ub}@{par}

@{"IEvent" link "MacrosIEvent"}@{par}
@{"Eject" link "MacrosEject"}@{par}
@{"IRComSend" link "MacrosIRcomSend"}@{par}

@{JLEFT}
@{b}* Please note that the usage of these macros may cause trouble, because they ignore several
system programming rules.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "MacrosArguments" "Macros - The Arguments"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "The Argumente"}

The arguments follow the same rules like the command arguments under AmigaDos.
Please refer your dos manual for further information.@{par}

If you want to specify spaces within strings it's required to enclose the string
with brackets.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosScreenNext" "Macros - ScreenNext"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ScreenNext"}

This function forces the next screen to front.

@endnode
@node "MacrosScreenPrev" "Macros - ScreenPrev"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ScreenPrev"}

This function forces the previous screen to front.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWBToFront" "Macros - WBToFront"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WBToFront"}

By using this command you force the workbench screen to front. (LCOMMAND n).@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

WBToFront@{par}

Creates a "LCOMMAND n" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowBottomLeft" "Macros - WindowBottomLeft"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowBottomLeft"}

The active window will be moved into the left bottom edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowBottomRight" "Macros - WindowBottomRight"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowBottomRight"}

The active window will be moved into the right bottom edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowCenter" "Macros - WindowCenter"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowCenter"}

The active window will centered.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowClose" "Macros - WindowClose"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowClose"}

The active window will close. Of course the window must have a close button.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowControl" "Macros - WindowControl"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowControl"}

@{b}This macro is only available when using MorphOS!@{ub}@{par}

By using this command you can hide and unhide windows.@{par}

HIDE/S,HIDEALL/S,HIDEOTHER/S,HIDEAPP/S,HIDEAPPOTHER/S,SHOW/S,SHOWALL/S,SHOWOTHER/S,SHOWAPP/S,SHOWAPPOTHER/S"@{par}

HIDE/S: The active window will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEALL/S: All windows will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEOTHER/S: All windows beside the active one will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEAPP/S: All windows of the same application will be hidden.@{par}

HIDEAPPOTHER/S: All windows which are not related to the tame application will be hidden.@{par}

SHOW/S: The active window will be visible again.@{par}

SHOWALL/S: All windows will be visible again.@{par}

SHOWOTHER/S: All windows beside the active will be visible again.@{par}

SHOWAPP/S: All windows that are owned by the same application will be visible.@{par}

SHOWAPPOTHER/S: All windows that are not owned by the same application will be visible.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowMaximise" "Macros - WindowMaximise"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowMaximise"}

Maximises the active window.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowMinimise" "Macros - WindowMinimise"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowMinimise"}

Minimises the active window.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowMove" "Macros - WindowMove"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowMove"}

By using this function it's possible to move the active window. Some Arguments are available to
selection all options:@{par}

CENTER/S,LEFT/S,UP/S,RIGHT/S,DOWN/S,PLEFT/K/N,PUP/K/N,PRIGHT/K/N,PDOWN/K/N@{par}

CENTER/S does what it says. The direction switches just move the window to the
screen border. The P#? directions move the window by a specific number of
pixel.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

WindowMove Center PLeft 10@{par}

Centres the window and moves it 10 pixel to the left.@{par}

WindowMove Up Left PDown 20 PRight 10@{par}

This will move the window into the left top edge of the screen and 20 pixel down and 10 pixel to
the right.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowNext" "Macros - WindowNext"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowNext"}

This function forces the next window to be activated.@{par}

NOTOFRONT/S,ALLOWWB/S,HIDE/S@{par}

NOTOFRONT simply causes the window will be activated, but not pulled to front.

ALLOWWB allows to browse though workbench windows which are borderless and/or in
background, like standard workbench screen window.@{par}

HIDE: The current window will be hidden. @{b}MorphOS only@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowPrev" "Macros - WindowPrev"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowPrev"}

This function forces the prev window to be activated.@{par}

NOTOFRONT/S,ALLOWWB/S,HIDE/S@{par}

NOTOFRONT simply causes the window will be activated, but not pulled to front.

ALLOWWB allows to browse though workbench windows which are borderless and/or in
background, like standard workbench screen window.@{par}

HIDE: The current window will be hidden. @{b}MorphOS only@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowToBack" "Macros - WindowToBack"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowToBack"}

The active window will be pushed to the back. It stays selected.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowToFront" "Macros - WindowToFront"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowToFront"}

The active window will be moved to the front. It stays selected.

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowTopLeft" "Macros - WindowTopLeft"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowTopLeft"}

The active window will be moved into the top left edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowTopRight" "Macros - WindowTopRight"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowTopRight"}

The active window will be moved into the top right edge of the screen.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWindowZip" "Macros - WindowZip"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WindowZip"}

The active window will be maximised or minimised, depending on it's previous state.

@endnode
@node "MacrosReqOk" "Macros - ReqOk"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ReqOk"}

By using this command you can confirm a requester. (LCOMMAND c).@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

ReqOk@{par}

Creates a "LCOMMAND c" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosReqCancel" "Macros - ReqCancel"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ReqCancel"}

By using this command you can abort a requester. (LCOMMAND v).@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

ReqCancel@{par}

Creates a "LCOMMAND v" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosMouseClick" "Macros - MouseClick"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "MouseClick"}

This command allows to simulated mouse buttons. Several options are available:@{par}

MIDDLE/S,RIGHT/S,SINGLE/S@{par}

Without arguments MouseClick is performing a double click with the left mouse button. By adding
"MIDDLE" and "RIGHT" you can select other buttons. SINGLE turns the double click into a single
click.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosMouseMove" "Macros - MouseMove"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "MouseMove"}

This command allows to move the mouse pointer without touching the mouse. Just use the following
options:@{par}

LEFT/K/N,RIGHT/K/N,UP/K/N,DOWN/K/N@{par}

Without arguments the mouse pointer isn't moving. Please note that depending on the screen mode the
mouse steps may be reduced by the input system. This may cause that only each second pixel is moving
the pointer.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

MouseMove Left 10 Up 10@{par}

The mouse pointer is moving 10 pixel to the left and 10 pixel up.@{par}

MouseMove Right 10 Up 15@{par}

The mouse pointer is moving 10 pixel right and 15 pixel up.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosColdReboot" "Macros - ColdReboot"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "ColdReboot"}

This command will reboot your system and all reset resident data (viruses, RAD, OS3.x
ROM Updates) will be kicked out of memory.@{par}

After rebooting the system is in the same state as if you turned it off and on again!@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosWarmReboot" "Macros - WarmReboot"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "WarmReboot"}

This command restarts your system!

@endnode
@node "MacrosIEvent" "Macros - IEvent"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "IEvent"}

IEvent is the system name for "input event". By using this command you can
simulate input sequences. Let's say it easy: You can create one or more keys by
using this command.@{par}

This command requires some @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}:@{par}

CLASS/K/A,STREAM/K,STRING/K,CODE/K,QUALIFIER/K,-QUALIFIER/K,X/K,Y/K,
LSHIFT/S,RSHIFT/S,CAPSLOCK/S,CONTROL/S,LALT/S,RALT/S,LCOMMAND/S,RCOMMAND/S,
NUMERICPAD/S,REPEAT/S,INTERRUPT/S,MULTIBROADCAST/S,MIDBUTTON/S,RBUTTON/S,LEFTBUTTON/S,
-LSHIFT/S,-RSHIFT/S,-CAPSLOCK/S,-CONTROL/S,-LALT/S,-RALT/S,-LCOMMAND/S,-RCOMMAND/S,
-NUMERICPAD/S,-REPEAT/S,-INTERRUPT/S,-MULTIBROADCAST/S,-MIDBUTTON/S,-RBUTTON/S,-LEFTBUTTON/S

@{MS "CLASS"}

Describes the argument type. Currently only "RAWKEY" and "RAWMOUSE".

@{MS "STRING"}

STRING is only valid when using the keyboard class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"}. "String hello" creates the keyboard
input "hello". @{b}Please note that the whole string will be translated into real key codes by the system.
This causes a delay before output.@{ub}

@{MS "STREAM"}

STREAM is only valid when using the keyboard class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"}. The "text" must be specified as hex string.
STREAM "20" creates a small "a". Qualifier code are special, because they are processed immediately.
STREAM "6120" creates a "A", because 61 is the code for the left shift key. All following key codes
are processed with the shift key until you release shift by using "E1", which is the rawkey code for
releasing the left shift key.

@{MS "CODE"}

A single IEvent information. The specific values are depending on the used class. "69" represents the
right mouse button in the "RawMouse" class. Within the rawkey class only raw key codes are valid.

@{MS "QUALIFIER"}

This 16 bit value allows to set one or more specific qualifiers. When using the "String" mode this value
isn't effective.

@{MS "-QUALIFIER"}

Here it's possible to specify one or more specific qualifier to pass through. E.g. if the LSHIFT bit is
set, the current state of the left shift key is used.

@{MS "X and Y"}

These are the delta cords. When using the RAWMOUSE mode the mouse is moving by the number of pixel
specified here. To move the mouse left or up it's required to specify negativ values. (e.g. fffe)

@{MS "All the other switches"}

The other switches are working exact like the "Qualifier" or "-Qualifier" versions. This is more
user friendly than typing the hex values. You can use any combination of qualifier.

Examples:@{par}

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} String "Guido Mersmann"@{par}

creates the keyboard input "Guido Mersmann"@{par}

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} Stream "4c4c"@{par}

creates two "cursor up" keys.@{par}

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} Stream "612020E120"@{par}

This one is a little more komplex. "61" is the @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} code for the left shift key. The next two values are "20".
These are creating two "a"s. Then an "E1" is following. It's the shift key again, but this time the release
version (61+80). The last "a" ("20") is small again. The output is "AAa". I know this isn't the easiest way to
create this output, but it's just an example.

IEvent Class @{"RAWKEY" link "FAQSRAW"} Stream "4c4c" -lshift@{par}

this one creates two "cursor up". If the left shift key is pressed two "shift cursor up" will
be created"@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosEject" "Macros - Eject"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Eject"}

By using this command you can control CD/DVD/ZIP/SCSI drives media and trays.@{par}

This command requires some @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}:@{par}

DEVICE/A,UNIT/N,LOCK/S,UNLOCK/S,EJECT/S,LOAD/S,TOGGLE/S,JIFFIES/N

DEVICE/A        : Always needed! Specify drive name like "cd0:" or device name like "scsi.device".@{par}
UNIT/N          : device unit. Only needed when using device name with the DEVICE option. Default is 0.@{par}
LOCK/S          : Tray or media will be locked and can't be removed/opened.@{par}
UNLOCK/S        : Tray or media gets unlocked and can be removed/opened again.@{par}
EJECT/S         : Ejects media or opens drive tray.@{par}
LOAD/S          : Media/tray gets sucked in.@{par}
TOGGLE/S        : Media/tray will change it's current state. (Default if no other command is selected).@{par}
JIFFIES/S       : If TOGGLE is failing for some reason try to change the default value of 10..@{par}

Examples:@{par}

Eject cd0:@{par}

Opens tray of cd drive if it's closed. If it's closed it will be opened.@{par}

Eject cd0: unlock toggle lock@{par}

Tray gets unlocked, then the tray state changes from open to close or vice
versa and finally the tray gets locked again. You can't open the tray by using the
drives eject button, because it stays locked.@{par}

Eject zip:@{par}

ZIP drives do not support media load, so this option allows to just eject it.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosCut" "Macros - Cut"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Cut"}

By using this command you can create a clipboard cut event.@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

Cut@{par}

Creates a "RCOMMAND x" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosCopy" "Macros - Copy"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Copy"}

By using this command you can create a clipboard copy event.@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

Copy@{par}

Creates a "RCOMMAND c" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosPaste" "Macros - Paste"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "Paste"}

By using this command you can create a clipboard paste event.@{par}

This command requires no @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"}!@{par}

Example:@{par}

Paste@{par}

Creates a "RCOMMAND v" input event.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MacrosIRComSend" "Macros - IRComSend"
@toc "Macros"

@{MS "IRComSend"}

This command allows to send out ir signals to television sets, cd, dvd players
and anything else which is listening to ir codes. This feature requires the
@{b}IRCom@{ub} driver and compatible hardware.@{par}

Some @{"arguments" link "MacrosArguments"} are required for operation:@{par}

UNIT/K/N, KEYS/A/M@{par}

UNIT/K/N     : Specifies the IRCom hardware number. Default is 0L. Only required when you're@{par}
               using more than one ircom compatible hardware@{par}

KEYS/A/M     : Here you can define one or more keys in IRCom format to send out.@{par}

For more information on IRCom and it's usage contault the IRCom Manual.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

IRComSend play\@cdplayer@{par}

Sends the "play" signal to the cd player. Of course the remote "cdplayer" and
the key "play" must be available within the ircom database.@{par}

IRComSend +10\@cdplayer 1\@cdplayer 2\@cdplayer@{par}

Send the +10 signal followed by an "1" and a "2". The CD player is selecting
track 12.@{par}

@endnode

